authorized subscribers using a global system for mobile communication core 
network.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Home Location Register (HLR) is a database that contains data regarding authorized subscribers using a global system for mobile communication (GSM) core network. The home location register stores information ranging from phone numbers to current location of the subscriber. Some data contained in the home location register include the mobile Station International Subscriber Directory Number (MSISDN) which is a list of the telephone numbers used by the subscriber and the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/imsi">International Mobile Subscriber Identity (IMSI)</a> which is a unique identifier of each subscriber identity module (SIM) and is the primary key for each HLR record of each subscriber.</p><p class="">Cell phones and their corresponding SIMs are mostly on the move. The HLR is used to identify their last known location. This information is updated each time the device is transferred in to another location. The HLR also facilitates Short message services (SMS) by scanning through the HLR to identify the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/mobile-switching-center">mobile switching center (MSC)</a> currently used by the receiving party. If the recipient is reported as not available by the receiving MSC, a message waiting flag is sent on the HLR. The message is then delivered once the recipient is located on any MSC.</p><p class="">Other mobile components associated with the HLR include the gateway mobile switching center (G-MSC), the authentication center (AUC) and the visitor location register (VLR).</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Full Duplex</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:48:20 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/full-duplex</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4e1872483a33b729d137</guid><description><![CDATA[Full Duplex (FDX) is a type of communication system. In full duplex, there 
is a two-way communication between the sender and the receiver.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Full Duplex (FDX) is a type of communication system. In full duplex, there is a two-way communication between the sender and the receiver. The sender and the receiver can send and receive messages simultaneously. A typical example of a full duplex communication system are telephones. Communication on a telephone can go both ways and both communicating parties can transmit their messages at the same time. In the IT world, most network protocols work on the full-duplex mode. This enables connected devices to send and receive data being transmitted at the same time.</p><p class="">In full duplex, transmission can be separated in time using the Time Division Duplex (TDD) or <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/frequency">frequency</a> using the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/frequency-division-duplex">Frequency Division Duplex (FDD)</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>HSDPA</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:47:38 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/hsdpa</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4deb7e6e4004623b8cd2</guid><description><![CDATA[High speed downlink packet access (HSDPA), also known as 3.5G is an 
improved third generation telecommunication protocol.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">High speed downlink packet access (HSDPA), also known as 3.5G is an improved third generation telecommunication protocol. It is an advancement of the Universal Mobile Telecommunication System (UTMS) radio which provides higher data capacity and increased transfer rates. HSDPA was the first implementation of High-Speed Packet Access (HSPA). it enabled high-speed transfer to the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/downlink">downlink</a> of speed of up to 14 Mbps which are shared among users. </p><p class="">HSDPA also provided reduced latency, thereby reducing the cost of data transfer. HSDPA introduced a new high-speed downlink channel which is distributed among users. It also provided a shorter transmission duration of 2 milliseconds compared to the initial 10 ms, which was used by UTMS release 99. HSDPA also uses faster data traffic scheduling feature that allows it to allocate a large <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/cell">cell </a>capacity to a user to provide high-speed data in a short time. It also uses an advanced modulation and coding technique and provides faster retransmission of packets containing errors. HSDPA uses these features to provide a high data rate to mobile users.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Visitor Location Register</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:46:30 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/visitor-location-register</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4da610e9936d8b33a821</guid><description><![CDATA[The visitor location register (VLR) is a database which houses information 
about the subscribers whom have roamed within a mobile switching center’s 
(MSC) location area.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">The visitor location register (VLR) is a database which houses information about the subscribers whom have roamed within a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/mobile-switching-center">mobile switching center’s (MSC)</a> location area. The VLR database helps reduce the number of queries sent to the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/home-location-register-hlr">home location register (HLR)</a> which contains the permanent records of mobile subscribers.</p><p class="">A VLR database contains fields similar to the HLR. The information stored in the VLR is gotten from the HLR or collected by the MSC. The main difference being that the HLR is a more permanent record as the record in a VLR is deleted once the subscriber moves to another MSC.</p><p class="">A VLR register monitors the subscriber’s location in its jurisdiction, determines access of a particular service to a user, allocates roaming numbers during incoming calls, deletes records of inactive users and accepts information passed to it by the HLR.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Half Duplex</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:45:32 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/half-duplex</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4d6baa4807177d2f08df</guid><description><![CDATA[Half Duplex (HDX) is a type of communication system. In half duplex, there 
is a two-way communication between the sender and the receiver.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Half Duplex (HDX) is a type of communication system. In half duplex, there is a two-way communication between the sender and the receiver. The sender and the receiver can both receive and send messages. The transmission between communicating parties can only be done one after the other. That is, once one end is transmitting, the other hand has to wait for the transmission to be completed before initiating a transmission. This type of communication system is used in situation where communication in both directions at the same time is not necessary. A typical example of a half-duplex communication system is a walkie talkie. A walkie talkie enables users to communicate back and forth on a specific radio frequency. However, since a walkie talkie function in half-duplex mode, only one person can speak at a time.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>5G</title><category>Network Generations</category><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:44:03 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/5g</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4ce44547e700d1cf46cf</guid><description><![CDATA[5G is the 5th generation mobile network. It is a new global wireless 
standard after 1G, 2G, 3G, and 4G networks.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">5G is the 5th generation mobile network. It is a new global wireless standard after 1G, <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/2g">2G</a>, <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/3g">3G</a>, and <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/4g">4G</a> networks. 5G enables a new kind of network that connects virtually everyone and everything together including machines, objects, and devices. 5G wireless technology is meant to deliver higher multi-Gbps peak data speeds, ultra-low latency, more reliability, massive network capacity, increased availability, and a more uniform user experience to more users. Higher performance and improved efficiency empower new user experiences and connects new industries.</p><p class="">5G is a unified, more capable air interface. It has been designed with an extended capacity to enable next-generation user experiences, empower new deployment models and deliver new services. With high speeds, superior reliability and negligible latency, 5G will expand the mobile ecosystem into new realms. 5G will impact every industry, making safer transportation, remote healthcare, precision agriculture, digitized logistics and more reality.</p><p class="">5G is said function at a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/bandwidth">bandwidth</a> greater than 1Gbps with Latency less than 10 seconds and an average speed of 200mbps. 5G is used across three main types of connected services, including enhanced mobile broadband, mission-critical communications, and IoT. 5G operates on three different spectrum bands, the Low-band spectrum, Mid-band spectrum, and High-band spectrum.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Embedded SIM</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:42:20 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/embedded-sim</