(eUICC) is a rewritable Subscriber Identifier Module (SIM) card that is 
embedded directly in to an IoT device]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">An Embedded-SIM (eSIM) or embedded Universal Integrated Circuit Card (eUICC) is a rewritable Subscriber Identifier Module (SIM) card that is embedded directly in to an IoT device. The SIM stores all relevant information necessary to identify and authenticated the subscriber.</p><p class="">An eSIM provides flexibility to choose between operators as devices can store multiple operator profiles and switch between them remotely. eSIM also has a dual function that allows end-users have dual SIMs. eSIM is a global specification by the GSMA. GSMA define eSIM as a revolution for the next generation of connected computer devices and networking solutions. The universal approach of eSIM technology will grow Internet of Things application by providing a global platform where a new range of products can be developed based on the embedded SIM architecture.</p><p class="">eSIM provides the same electrical interface as the conventional SIM card sizes, 2FF. 3FF, 4FF. The only difference is that eSIMs are soldered to a circuit board by the manufacturers. The eSIM format is designated by MFF2.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Firewall</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:41:03 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/firewall</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4c602405f70f2a6a4ba3</guid><description><![CDATA[A firewall is a network security system that prevents unauthorized users 
from having access to a network.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">A firewall is a network security system that prevents unauthorized users from having access to a network. Firewall analyses network traffic and decides whether to allow or deny access to specific network traffic based on pre-defined network security rules. Firewall can be implemented as a hardware or a software or a combination of both. Firewall is usually categorized as network-based firewall and host-based firewall.</p><p class="">Network based firewall is usually implemented at the edge between a local network and the internet. They are software applications running on networking devices or hardware-based firewall appliances. Network firewall filters all traffic coming in and going out of a network and allows only packets that match the pre-defined rules. Network based firewall can be stateful or stateless.</p><p class="">Host- based firewalls run on host devices as a daemon or service or an endpoint security agent and filters traffic in and out of the device. Traffic in host-based firewalls is filtered based on processes carried out, unlike network-based firewall that filters based on ports. Host firewalls are mostly used alongside network firewalls as host firewalls are prone to process exploitation attacks.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>4G</title><category>Network Generations</category><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:39:24 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/4g</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4bf87e6e4004623b7403</guid><description><![CDATA[4G is the fourth generation of broadband cellular network technology, 
succeeding 3G. 4G works much in the same way as 3G, but simply faster.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">4G is the fourth generation of broadband cellular network technology, succeeding <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/3g">3G</a>. 4G works much in the same way as 3G, but simply faster. Using high-speed download and upload packets, 4G allows you to access broadband style speeds whilst away from your Wi-Fi.&nbsp;</p><p class="">One of the principal differences between 4G and 3G models is the speed at which they can download files from the internet. A typical 3G phone can connect to the internet at a maximum speed of up to 21Mbps, whereas a 4G phone can do so at theoretical maximum speeds of 300Mbps, also 4G is entirely IP based, which means it uses internet protocols even for voice data. Its higher data speeds could make smartphones and M2M devices much more comparable to PCs, giving them better capabilities.</p><p class="">4G systems provide capabilities that are specified by ITU in international Mobile Telecommunications Advanced (IMT-advanced). WiMax and <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/lte">LTE</a> are regarded as stopgaps as they do not comply with the requirement of 1Gbps for stationary reception and 100mbps for mobile reception.&nbsp;LTE is advertised as 4G by many network providers.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Base Station Controller</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:38:13 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/base-station-controller</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4bb80e9a5e1d011d5ead</guid><description><![CDATA[A Base Station controller (BSC) is a telecommunication network component 
responsible for the control of one or more Base Transceiver Stations (BTS).]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">A Base Station controller (BSC) is a telecommunication network component responsible for the control of one or more Base Transceiver Stations (BTS). The BSC controls the activities of the BTS. The BSC is referred to as a mediator and physical link between the BTS and the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/mobile-switching-center">Mobile Switching Center (MSC)</a>. It allocates radio channels, receives measurement from mobile devices, controls BTS to BTS handover and call setup. The BSC stores data, which includes the frequency of the carrier, the frequency hopping list and power levels. The BSC manages station activity thereby reducing the workload of the MSC which then focuses on handling critical tasks suck as traffic and database management. The BSC also act as a translator which converts the 13kbps voice frequency used by radio links to a 64kbps frequency understood by the public Switched Telephone Network (PSDN).</p><p class="">The BSC is the most robust equipment of the Base Station Subsystem (BSS). It often functions in a distributed system architecture where redundancy is carried out to its functional parts to avoid downtime of the BSC and ensure its constant availability in the event of various faults that may arise.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Base Station</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:37:14 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/base-station</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4b8117f0472d0282591c</guid><description><![CDATA[A base station is a radio receiver which may have one or multiple antenna. 
It was first used in mobile telecommunication networks.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">A base station is a radio receiver which may have one or multiple antenna. It was first used in mobile telecommunication networks. The base station is responsible for maintaining communication between the network and the users, and also among users. The equipment works with a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/mobile-switching-center">mobile switching station</a> which is responsible for connecting cellular calls to the public switched telephone network (PSTN). The geographical area covered by a base station is referred to as a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/cell">cell</a>. A single base station broadly extends the reach of a telecommunication company. A base station is company specific, but competing telecommunication companies can have their individual base stations on a physical site.</p><p class="">In terms of wireless communication, a base station is a transceiver that connects networking devices together a well as connecting the devices to the internet. In a computer network, a base station is transceiver that connects devices together on a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/local-area-network">local area network</a> and possibly connecting the devices to another local area network.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Bandwidth</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:36:22 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/bandwidth</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4b4b8b60070e53f6b3e1</guid><description><![CDATA[Bandwidth is the maximum amount of data that can be transmitted over a 
network path in a fixed amount of time.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Bandwidth is the maximum amount of data that can be transmitted over a network path in a fixed amount of time. Bandwidth is measured in bits per second (bps). The bandwidth of a network affects the transmission capacity of a connection and is therefore important in determining the quality and speed of a network connection.&nbsp;</p><p class="">The bandwidth of a network describes the network speed, but it does not measure how fast data is transmitted over the network. Bandwidth measures how much data can be transmitted over a network at a particular time. Data flows through multiple networks over the internet. The network with the smallest bandwidth is referred to as the bottleneck of the transmission. Typically, the backbone connection and connections between servers have the most bandwidth, therefore, they are rarely bottlenecks. The most common bottleneck in internet transmission is usually the connection between the ISP and the user.</p><p class="">In signal processing, bandwidth is used to refer to a range of frequencies that are used in transmitting a signal. This type of bandwidth is measured in hertz (Hz).</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Backhaul</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:35:07 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/backhaul</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4af9761f950f7d6060b2</guid><description><![CDATA[Backhaul in terms of telecommunication refers to the physical part of a 
network that is in between the backbone of the network and the individual 
local networks.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Backhaul in terms of telecommunication refers to the physical part of a network that is in between the backbone of the network and the individual local networks or a channel in which satellite signals are sent from which the signal can be distributed over a network. Backhaul facilitates the transmission of signal - voice and data - from the core network to other smaller networks and vice versa. A backhaul could be wired, fiber optics or wireless.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Code Division Multiple Access (CDMA)</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:34:01 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/cdma</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4abf599ee776a48a1a32</guid><description><![CDATA[Code division multiple access (CDMA) is a multiple access scheme that 
relies on direct sequence spread spectrum communication techniques to 
facilitate radio communication.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Code division multiple access (CDMA) is a multiple access scheme that relies on direct sequence spread spectrum communication techniques to facilitate radio communication. CDMA uses multi access which allows several transmitters to send information at the same time over a single channel and with this, optimizes <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/bandwidth">bandwidth</a>.&nbsp;</p><p class="">CDMA technology was originally deployed as an encryption tool for the US Army during the Vietnam war. CDMA method of transmission uses coding to separate different transmissions. Using CDMA, data is transmitted in the form of noise, making it difficult to jam and also to decipher without the appropriate transmission codes. CDMA uses a Direct Sequence Spread Spectrum (DSSS) property where the transmitter and the receiver must use the same spreading code to transmit data. This ensured the transmission could not be decoded thereby providing room for a variety of user to transmit data over the same channel without interference.</p><p class="">CDMA has been widely deployed as the access method by many mobile phone standards. IS-95 also called CDMAone was deployed as a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/2g">2G</a> mobile telecommunication standard for transmitting voice, data and signaling data (dialed telephone numbers). Also, CDMA2000 was deployed as a backward compatible replacement for the IS-95. CDMA2000 was deployed on the <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/3g">3G</a> network to provide multi access for data, signaling data and voice.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Cellular network</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 May 2022 05:32:24 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/cellular-network</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627b4a682405f70f2a6a28eb</guid><description><![CDATA[Cellular Network also referred to as a mobile network is a network of 
radios distributed over land. These networks are distributed by cells.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Cellular Network also referred to as a mobile network is a network of radios distributed over land. These networks are distributed by cells. These cells contain at least one fixed transceiver which provides network coverage for the range in which it covers. In cellular communication, neighboring cells use different sets of frequencies to avoid interference. A collection of cells provides a wholistic network coverage for a mobile network. This provides a means in which end user mobile devices can communicate even when moving through cells.</p><p class="">One key characteristic of a cellular network is the ability to re-use frequencies, providing an increased coverage and capacity. The factors that govern frequency reuse are the reuse distance, which states the distance between cells – and the reuse factor – which is the rate at which a frequency can be used in a network. To distinguish cellular signals from other transmitters, cellular networks use a variety of technology which include Frequency Division Multiple Access (FDMA), Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA) and Code division Multiple Access (CDMA).</p><p class="">Cellular networks function in a hierarchical system. A cellular network consists of a Base station transceiver (BTS) which routes calls from mobile devices to its corresponding Base station controller (BSC). The BSC works together with the Mobile Switching center (MSC) to interface with the public switched telephone network (PSTN), the visitor location register (VLR) and the home location register (HLR) to route calls over different base stations.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Cell</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 17:43:53 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/cell</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627aa44d298bff05dcd63c72</guid><description><![CDATA[A cell is a geographical area covered by the frequency emitted by a base 
station in a cellular network. The elements that transmit this frequency is 
called a cell site.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">A cell is a geographical area covered by the frequency emitted by a <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/base-station">base station</a> in a cellular network. The elements that transmit this <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/frequency">frequency</a> is called a cell site. The cell provided by a cell site can range from a few kilometers to thousands of kilometers in diameter, depending on the terrain, the technology being deployed and the transmission power of the cell site. A host of cell sites form a cell system.</p><p class="">In telecommunication, each cell is given a number of frequencies or channels. Different channels are used between neighbor cells to avoid interference and provide quality of data transmission. These frequencies are then used by many mobile devices or subscribers to carry out simultaneous conversations.&nbsp;</p><p class="">Cells can be classified based on their range and capacity. Macro cells are large cells which are usually used in remote, sparsely populated areas these cells have a high reach. Micro cells are utilized in densely populated areas and have a low reach of about 1 kilometer. Other types of cells include Pico cells which are normally used to cover a small area like buildings or blind spots of bigger cells, selective cells, which are a 360-degree coverage cell and umbrella cells used to cushion the effect of hand overs between micro cells.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 17:43:07 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627aa41cd4313114fc1eac67</guid><description><![CDATA[Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is a network management protocol 
that provides a framework that allows the allocation of internet protocol 
(IP) addresses.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is a network management protocol that provides a framework that allows the allocation of internet protocol (IP) addresses and other network configuration information – subnet mask and default gateway – to host devices on a TCP/IP network. A DHCP server enables host devices to request IP addresses and other networking parameters automatically. This eliminates the need for the network administrator or the user to manually input networking parameters on connected host devices to establish communication.</p><p class="">Devices communicate within and across a network using the internet protocol. A DHCP server can manage the allocation of these IP addresses on a local network. DHCP operates based on a client-sever model. When a host device connects to a network, the DHCP client sends a broadcast requesting an IP allocation (lease). The DHCP server then replies with network configuration parameters as well as a time frame for the lease of the address as predefined by the administrator. In large and complex networks, a DHCP relay can be configured to manage DHCP client and server request across subnets. DHCP can be implemented on IPv4 and IPv6 and is defined by RFC 2131.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Ethernet</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 17:42:23 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/ethernet</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627aa3f778a85f5a7a44036d</guid><description><![CDATA[Ethernet is the most common type of Local Area Network (LAN) Connection in 
use today. Ethernet connects devices on a wired LAN, enabling them to 
communicate with each other using a common protocol.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Ethernet is the most common type of <a href="https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/local-area-network">Local Area Network (LAN)</a> Connection in use today. Ethernet connects devices on a wired LAN, enabling them to communicate with each other using a common protocol. An Ethernet cable is the physical wiring connected to communicating devices, over which data frames can be transmitted. Ethernet was introduced in 1980 and the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) defined Ethernet standard as 802.3 in 1983. Over time, Ethernet made obsolete other competing wired LAN technology like Token ring designed by IBM, FDDI and ARCNET. As at the year 2010, the Ethernet equipment market was estimated at $16 billion per year.</p><p class="">Compared to the wireless local area network (WLAN), the ethernet is essentially faster, providing speed from 10mbps – which is the original data rate – to newer versions of Ethernet (Fast Ethernet) which supports data transfer rate of up to 100mbps, a further development introduced Gigabit Ethernet which has a transmission rate between 1Gbps to 10Gbps based on the evolving Ethernet cable technology implemented (cat5, cat5e or cat6). Ethernet is less vulnerable to disruption.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Encryption</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 17:41:27 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/encryption</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627aa3b9d54f7f1f45f85281</guid><description><![CDATA[Encryption is the method of encoding information. The process of encrypting 
and decrypting information is known as cryptography.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Encryption is the method of encoding information. In encryption, plain text – which is the actual representation of the information – is passed through an algorithm to produce a ciphertext – which is an alternative form of the actual information. Encryption ensures that only authorized parties can decipher the ciphertext to recreate the plain text. The process of encrypting and decrypting information is known as cryptography. Encryption uses an algorithm or a cipher which includes a variable. This variable (Key) is what makes the cipher unique. A combination of knowing the algorithm used and the key used as a variable is what makes encryption such a valuable security tool.</p><p class="">Encryption has long been implemented by the military for secure communication. It is also being used to secure data in transit on a network. There are two types of encryption. Symmetric encryption and asymmetric encryption.</p><p class="">In symmetric encryption, the encryption and decryption keys are the same. This key is shared between communicating parties. The weak point of this encryption is the transfer of keys between the parties involved. This encryption is best used for one-to-one sharing.</p><p class="">Asymmetric encryption (public key encryption), is a type of encryption where the encryption key is published and can be viewed by everyone but the decryption key is private and can only be accessed by the recipient.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Frequency</title><dc:creator>Roel van der Meer</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 17:40:36 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.simbase.com/iot-glossary-dictionary/frequency</link><guid isPermaLink="false">6267c7fbad6356776aa08e6d:627a8b5ac972db44a2d6384a:627aa386d5d35c3a929744a7</guid><description><![CDATA[Frequency is defined as the number of cycles per unit time. Frequency is 
usually used to represent short and fast waves like sound and radio 
signals.]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="">Frequency is defined as the number of cycles per unit time. Frequency is usually used to represent short and fast waves like sound and radio signals. Frequency is measured in Hertz in recognition of a German scholar Heinrich Rudolf Hertz. Hertz (Hz) is the number of occurrences of an event per second. If it takes ½ second for a total occurrence of an event, then the frequency is said to be 2Hz. 1 thousand Hz is represented as 1 kilohertz (1 KHz) 1 million hertz is 1 megahertz (1 MHz) and 1 billion hertz is 1 gigahertz (1 GHz). Frequency is usually represented by <em>f </em>and the Greek letters nu (ν) – often used to specify electromagnetic waves like light – and omega (ω) – used to define angular frequency (which is how many revolutions occur in radian per unit time).</p>]]></content:encoded></item></channel></rss>